🚀 Day 02 — Linux File Permissions & Ownership

Understanding Linux permissions is one of the most important skills for every DevOps Engineer.

📌 What are Linux Permissions?

Linux is a multi-user operating system.
Permissions control:

👤 Who can access files
✏️ Who can modify files
▶️ Who can execute files

Permissions improve:

🔐 Security
🛡️ Access control
⚙️ System management
📂 Types of Permissions

Linux has 3 basic permissions:

Symbol	Permission	Meaning
r	Read	View file contents
w	Write	Modify file
x	Execute	Run file/program
👥 Permission Categories

Permissions are assigned to 3 groups:

Category	Meaning
👤 User (u)	File owner
👥 Group (g)	Group users
🌍 Others (o)	Everyone else
🔍 Viewing File Permissions
Command
ls -l
Example Output
-rw-r--r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu 0 May 21 notes.txt
🧠 Understanding Permission Structure
-rw-r--r--

Breakdown:

Part	Meaning
-	File type
rw-	User permissions
r--	Group permissions
r--	Others permissions
📘 Permission Meaning
Permission	Value
r	4
w	2
x	1
🔢 Numeric Permission Method
Number	Permission
7	rwx
6	rw-
5	r-x
4	r--
⚙️ chmod Command
📌 Definition

chmod changes file permissions.

🛠️ Syntax
chmod permissions filename
✅ Example 1 — Give Full Permission
chmod 777 notes.txt
Meaning
User	Group	Others
rwx	rwx	rwx

⚠️ Everyone gets full access.

✅ Example 2 — Owner Full Access Only
chmod 700 script.sh
Meaning
User	Group	Others
rwx	---	---

🔐 Only owner can access.

✅ Example 3 — Common Secure Permission
chmod 644 notes.txt
Meaning
User	Group	Others
rw-	r--	r--

📖 Owner can edit, others can only read.

👑 chown Command
📌 Definition

chown changes file ownership.

🛠️ Syntax
chown username filename
✅ Example
chown ubuntu notes.txt

Owner becomes ubuntu.

👥 Change Group Ownership
chown ubuntu:devops notes.txt
🧑‍💻 whoami Command
📌 Definition

Displays current logged-in user.

🛠️ Syntax
whoami
Example
ubuntu
🆔 id Command
📌 Definition

